&lt;details open="open"&gt;
&lt;summary&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Notes - Slide 14&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Linked data is still too much like rocket science (üöÄ‚öóÔ∏è) because of all the architecture (üë©üèΩ‚ÄçüöÄüë∑‚ÄçüèóÔ∏èüè¢) astronauts.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.joelonsoftware.com/2001/04/21/dont-let-architecture-astronauts-scare-you/"&gt;Joel Splosky&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These are the people I call Architecture Astronauts. It‚Äôs very hard to get them to write code or design programs, because they won‚Äôt stop thinking about Architecture. They‚Äôre astronauts because they are above the oxygen level, I don‚Äôt know how they‚Äôre breathing. They tend to work for really big companies that can afford to have lots of unproductive people with really advanced degrees that don‚Äôt contribute to the bottom line.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There‚Äôs also religious aspect to some of this.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;hr/&gt;
&lt;section typeof='http://purl.org/ontology/bibo/Slide'&gt;
&lt;img src='blog/2018/10/sefton-ro2018/Slide15.png' alt='
Stop treating ontologies like https://www.joelonsoftware.com/2001/04/21/dont-let-architecture-astronauts-scare-you/
' title='
Stop treating ontologies like https://www.joelonsoftware.com/2001/04/21/dont-let-architecture-astronauts-scare-you/
' border='1'  width='85%'/&gt;
&lt;details open="open"&gt;
&lt;summary&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Notes - Slide 15&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We need to stop treating ontologies like toothbrushes (ie avoiding using other people‚Äôs) and get on with implementing usable systems.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&lt;hr/&gt;
&lt;section typeof='http://purl.org/ontology/bibo/Slide'&gt;
&lt;img src='blog/2018/10/sefton-ro2018/Slide16.png' alt='
&lt;p&gt;' title='&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;' border='1'  width='85%'/&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;details open="open"&gt;
&lt;summary&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Notes - Slide 16&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;/summary&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So I‚Äôll finish with a provocation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Do we really really need more complicated ontologies when you can describe the what where when and why of research data in a &lt;em&gt;useful&lt;/em&gt; way with schema.org and JSON-LD? We need to recruit content and get experience describing it, not wait.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/details&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
